	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=item.html?item=10441&mid=101679195487976>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=item.html?item=10441&mid=101679195487976>Pass</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=10441&mid=101679195487976#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Fri, Mar 22nd 5:15 AM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=37877><span id=Scholar>moritam</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>32 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.33]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>As a 52 monk I would pass this item to a hybrid class. The 10% to mend is totally useless after Mend (100). Anyone doing the Ring of Fire should have a skill of at least that.<br><br>For those who don't understand mend: Six real life minutes after using mend you can reuse mend any time after that. Before a skill of 100 one of three things will happen:<br>1) instant gain 25% hitpoints<br>2) nothing<br>3) instant loss 25% hitpoints (can kill you)<br><br>Once mend is above 100 only one thing happens:<br>1) instant gain 25% hitpoints, failure is impossible! (There is a way to fail but it's an ongoing bug people can learn to avoid.)<br><br>Higher skill does NOT add more hitpoints or decrease the repop time on mend. I think mend (100) is reachable at level 19.<br><br>52 Monk</p>&nbsp;<br></td></td></tr>
